				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I'll go with Pope Benedict XVI's (Joseph Cardinal Ratzinger) argument: if you believe something and I believe something that the precise opposite of what you believe, then one of us is wrong. For example, if I believe that Jesus is the Way, the Truth, and the Life, and you believe that you can reach nirvana through the Sevenfold Path, unless the two Paths are pretty much the same, then AT LEAST one of them is not true. OR the destinations are different. Both can be true at the same time only if they lead to different destinations. Otherwise, AT MOST one can be truth. AT LEAST one must be false. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Both can be false. All I've said is that so far, I've seen no evidence either way. I am not willing to commit to belief (and actions on those beliefs) in things I cannot know, but I won't discard them out of hand either.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Perhaps God will, since he is merciful, provide salvation to those that do not base their claims to salvation on faith in Jesus Christ. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I hope so, or the vast majority of the world's total population (past, present, and future) is going to be in Hell. A fine display of morality that is. <span style="font-style: italic">My</span> morals are better than that, and I refuse to believe I'm more morally centered than God (impossible by definition), so clearly the premise is false on its face. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Why does he (that does not believe on Jesus) stand condemned? The Epistle to the Romans by Paul provides a very through dissertation on the theology of Christianity and answers questions like these. Paul's argument is that we stand condemned without Jesus Christ for THREE reasons: 
<br />

<br />
1. Nature provides sufficient evidence of God to support belief in him. (Romans 1:18 through 2:11.) What is the consequence for rejecting this "self evident truth"? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
That's always been evidence enough for me. Not because of where we came from, but because of where we appear to be going.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> "28Furthermore, since they did not think it worthwhile to retain the knowledge of God, he gave them over to a depraved mind, to do what ought not to be done. 29They have become filled with every kind of wickedness, evil, greed and depravity. They are full of envy, murder, strife, deceit and malice. They are gossips, 30slanderers, Godhaters, insolent, arrogant and boastful; they invent ways of doing evil; they disobey their parents; 31they are senseless, faithless, heartless, ruthless. 32Although they know God's righteous decree that those who do such things deserve death, they not only continue to do these very things but also approve of those who practice them." Romans 1:28-32 </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Man is one fucked up creature. We know this. We don't need God to tell us what our own minds make plainly obvious. There are plenty of people who have overcome these basic human impulses, most of which are artifacts of our evolution. Some use religion to do it, others can do it on their own. It would seem to be wiser to make judgements based on a man's ability to master himself, regardless of the methodology used, than to base it on what belief structures he follows.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> 2. Paul also argues that those who judge others are aware of the expectation that they should live righteously. (Romans 2:1-11) What is the consequence for judging others while not condemning yourself? 
<br />

<br />
"So when you, a mere man, pass judgment on them and yet do the same things, do you think you will escape God's judgment?" Romans 2:3 
<br />

<br />
3. God's revealed Law describes expectations for his creation. Those that have HEARD the Law are directly responsible for obeying all of it. Some of those who have NOT HEARD the Law still act uprightly, essentially becoming a Law unto themselves. Others that see people acting uprightly know there is a Law because they see those people either acting according to the tenets of revealed Law or according to the tenets of unrevealed (but still consistent and True) Law and are now ALSO responsible for their behavior with respect to the law. (Romans 2:12-16). What is the consequence of ignoring this revelation--whether it comes from the written word of God or from the testimony of someone who lives rightly without observing the written Law?? 
<br />

<br />
"12All who sin apart from the law will also perish apart from the law, and all who sin under the law will be judged by the law. 13For it is not those who hear the law who are righteous in God's sight, but it is those who obey the law who will be declared righteous." Romans 2:12-13 </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Does that not say that God is more interested in the results than the methodology?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Paul goes further in the end of chapter 2 and in chapter 3 to contest Truth with the Jews. He essentially argues that if they try to stand on the special relationship between the Jewish nation and God AND THEN are immoral, not only do they mock God but "24As it is written: “God's name is blasphemed among the Gentiles because of you." Now that's something I know people on this board can sink their teeth into. Hypocrisy by both Jews AND Christians indeed causes God's name to be blasphemed by unbelievers...the Bible SAYS SO. (It says so in the context of bringing the hearts of believers to a conviction of immorality, which means their behavior is not acceptable to God, by the way.) </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
God doesn't bother me. His fan club, however, can get really fucking annoying at times.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> In chapter 3, Paul gets to the heart of his argument. Regardless of whether you are a Jew OR a Gentile (the Hebrew is Goyim and loosely translates "nations"), you are under sin. Paul uses a poignant passage from the Old Testament to make this point: 
<br />

<br />
" 9What shall we conclude then? Are we any better? Not at all! We have already made the charge that Jews and Gentiles alike are all under sin. 10As it is written: “There is no one righteous, not even one; 
<br />
11there is no one who understands, 
<br />
no one who seeks God. 12All have turned away, 
<br />
they have together become worthless; there is no one who does good, 
<br />
not even one.” 13“Their throats are open graves; 
<br />
their tongues practice deceit.” “The poison of vipers is on their lips.”[e] 
<br />
14“Their mouths are full of cursing and bitterness.” 15“Their feet are swift to shed blood; 
<br />
16ruin and misery mark their ways, 17and the way of peace they do not know.” 
<br />
18“There is no fear of God before their eyes.” " </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
This sounds to me like a lot of psychologically spooky language for controlling primitive people. It's a meaningless generalization to demonize the evil unbelievers in the eyes of the faithful.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I want to be rather clear about this. What this passage claims is that regardless of how much we dress up human achievement, IF God exists THEN all of our lives are purposeless when we pull away from him and seek to do our own thing. And this passage also claims that we ALL have turned away from God. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I don't view God and human achievement as mutually exclusive. As far as my own feelings on the matter I view them as the same thing. The good is what improves life overall, and the bad is what diminishes it. If you want to stick the name God on the good side of things, feel free. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> "19Now we know that whatever the law says, it says to those who are under the law, so that every mouth may be silenced and the whole world held accountable to God. 20Therefore no one will be declared righteous in his sight by observing the law; rather, through the law we become conscious of sin." 
<br />

<br />
This verse refutes the concept that if you live a "good enough" life you will be declared righteous. In fact, the fact that we fail in being good in ANY way is a demonstration of our rebellion against God. Everything we do to appear to be good is, essentially, putting lipstick on a pig. (No offense to those that believe pigs are lovable, smart creatures, but I've slopped pigs before and seeing them wallow in both the mud and their food causes me to believe that the lipstick makes them neither more sightly nor less smelly.) 
<br />

<br />
Paul isn't done. I know that most of us reading this would admit, if pressed in a corner, that we've messed up. In fact, most of us use that as an argument against God's judgement: everyone is messed up, so how can God fairly judge us all? 
<br />

<br />
"21But now a righteousness from God, apart from law, has been made known, to which the Law and the Prophets testify. 22This righteousness from God comes through faith in Jesus Christ to all who believe. There is no difference, 23for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God, 24and are justified freely by his grace through the redemption that came by Christ Jesus. 25God presented him as a sacrifice of atonement, through faith in his blood. He did this to demonstrate his justice, because in his forbearance he had left the sins committed beforehand unpunished– 26he did it to demonstrate his justice at the present time, so as to be just and the one who justifies those who have faith in Jesus." Romans 3:21-26 
<br />

<br />
Note that last verse...it isn't one you hear very much but I believe it answers the criticism of how can God be just if he judges everyone (since veryone sins.) The answer is that he presented himself as a sacrifice of atonement in order to demonstrate his justice. He left the sins committed before the sacrifice unpunished and showed forbearance so that he would be seen as completely just. He also did it so that anyone who has faith in Jesus can be justified. 
<br />

<br />
What, exactly, is the meaning of justified? It actually is a building term and several of the Prophets refer to the concept: a plumb bob, a standard, a straight wall. If you have ever used a plumb bob to build, you know that the plumb bob points to the local center of gravity, which in most cases is approximately the center of the earth. If you build straight up from that center of gravity, then your building resists gravity the best. When you find a wall is off center and tear it down and rebuild it to be on center with the plumb bob, it's called justifying. Our modern use of the term is used in word processing when you "left justify" or "right justify" a column of text. You're making the margins straight when you justify a column of text against a margin. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
A plumb bob is a plumb bob. They all point in the same direction. I see little point in arguing about the color of the different models.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> God is just because he has provided a plan of salvation and provided an atonement for sin...his Son Jesus. But ALL have sinned and fall short of the glory of God. Therefore ALL need this atonement and ALL need THIS salvation. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I've seen little evidence for this conclusion. Any religion that wants my belief will need to explain why exactly God is so bent on making salvation nearly impossible to accept for anyone with a rational mind. It makes no sense whatsoever to base salvation on belief without proof. None. I'm not even sure it makes sense to base salvation on belief in the first place. There are better criteria than that.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I realize that many who read this will disagree and will argue my points. I'm not interested in arguing the points. I've presented them as accurately as I know how as a contribution to the thread. I've argued many of the same points in the past against the writers here. I could have chosen to not post (and probably will return to being silent), but I pray that my reasoned presentation will prove of value to at least one reader. I have no interest in presenting my own beliefs, but as cogent and accurate a presentation of Biblical Christianity as possible. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
There's little point in arguing them. As a sales pitch, these religions suck, and always devolve into the Hank arguments presented earlier. No proof, no logic, no rationality, no fairness to everyone, no belief, case closed.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I return to do this for one reason and one reason only: it is unreasonable to claim that all religions are the same and based on the same truth. They differ too much in essential ways to hold that position. Perhaps the greatest blasphemy against God is to claim he's the same as the Allah of Islam, as Brahma, as Kali, as Odin, as Isis and Osiris, as Ishtar, as Zeus, as Mythras, as Mazda or...worst of all...Satan. Have the decency to use your minds and admit there is a difference or be silent. Decry them all as made up if you must, but don't claim they're all the same. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
They are all the same, but you're looking at it from the wrong angle to see that. All of them differ fantasitcally on the surface, until you peel away all of the @#%$ and simply take a basic look at how these religions instruct their faithful to think and act. That's where the similarities emerge. All of them are attempting to provide a solid moral compass, and help their faithful become better people. All of them are hopelessly plagued by the artifacts and beliefs of their times, and all of them are completely out of their depth in a modern world where scientific thinking is becoming dominant, because none of them stand up solidly in the face of reason, except perhaps Buddism (but then Buddism has nothing to do with God or salvation, either).
<br />

<br />
All religions fail. All were written by man. Even if they were divinely inspired, they have been kept by man for centuries, and altered by man for centuries. Even the Pope is still human, and he is subject to all of the failings of humanity. So it is with all of us. Choosing to believe in Jesus does not make you any less fallible than you were the day before. Any information that may have come directly from God has gone through countless humans before it reached us, and it has been tainted by their beliefs, colored by their prejudice, and misinterpreted by their hands. Just look at what journalists do today to the facts when presenting information. You can't possibly think the same things didn't happen back then.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> In closing (feel free to substitute your favorite belief system for the gods of your forefathers or the gods of the Amorites): 
<br />

<br />
"But if serving the LORD seems undesirable to you, then choose for yourselves this day whom you will serve, whether the gods your forefathers served beyond the River, or the gods of the Amorites, in whose land you are living. But as for me and my household, we will serve the LORD." Joshua 24:15 </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Also feel free to shed all of these ancient belief structures if they don't make any sense to you. Whatever works for you is all that matters. If Jesus works for you, good for you. For myself, I desire a religion that doesn't run screaming from reason, or paint God as a morally bankrupt individual. Any religion that treats believers and unbelievers differently fails on moral grounds, and any religion that presumes to know the mind of God or makes fantastic, unprovable claims fails the test of reason.
<br />

<br />
Any religion that excludes those who do not follow it as acceptable losses or lesser beings espouses morals that are simply not consistent with even man's own basic ideas of equality and fairness. If equality and fairness come from God, why isn't he following those principles himself?
<br />

<br />
Maybe it was a good idea at some point, but it's devolved into "them" and "us" just like everything else. Humans have a very serious limitation when it comes to reason... everything must fit into twos. Apparently we aren't wired for thinking in any other way. Good vs evil, love vs hate, saved vs damned, them vs us, right vs wrong, democrat vs republican, on and on it goes forever. How conceited we are to think things always work that way. As soon as any issue polarizes itself into two camps like that, the issue itself is destroyed and only two opposite sides remain, both willing to do and say anything to prove the other wrong. Reason flies right out the window.<br />
